The Antitrust and Monopoly Subcommittee of which I am chairman has obtained many facts about

24:28.760 --> 24:34.840
this vital industry over more than two years of difficult hearings. I have gathered together

24:34.840 --> 24:40.120
those particular facts which I think are most relevant to the issues raised by the present

24:40.120 --> 24:44.760
labor management dispute in the steel industry. And I agree with the President that it would be

24:44.760 --> 24:50.600
well to make as much information about this public as possible. And I'm glad to send such

24:50.600 --> 24:55.880
information as I have to the President. And I would like to report the primary facts that we

24:55.880 --> 25:02.120
have been able to obtain to you here today on the subject of wages and productivity in the steel

25:02.120 --> 25:09.480
industry. Wages in terms of average hourly earnings are somewhat higher in the steel industry than

25:09.640 --> 25:16.520
in any other American manufacturing industry with the exception of flat glass. Despite a short

25:16.520 --> 25:24.520
decline in steel operating rate from 85 percent in 1957 to only 61 percent in 1958,

25:25.320 --> 25:32.280
man-hour productivity measured on the basis of hours paid showed only a 3.2 percent decline.

25:32.920 --> 25:38.680
While based on hours worked it remained virtually unchanged. It would thus appear that

25:38.680 --> 25:44.680
improvements in efficiency were of sufficient magnitude to offset the decrease in productivity

25:45.240 --> 25:51.640
resulting from the lower levels of output. Now on the subject of cost and prices in the steel

25:51.640 --> 26:00.200
industry, the increase in steel prices in 1957 was about twice the amount of the increase in cost

26:00.760 --> 26:06.440
resulting from the wage adjustments call for in the contract between the steel companies and the

26:06.440 --> 26:12.200
United Steel Workers. Profits for the industry have generally been sufficient to enable the major

26:12.200 --> 26:18.600
steel companies to finance most of their expansion since World War II out of retained earnings.

26:19.240 --> 26:24.120
They have made little use of the vast amount of savings in the hands of the investing public

26:24.680 --> 26:31.000
as a source of funds to finance finance plant expansion and improvement. It is a consumer

26:31.000 --> 26:36.520
through the prices which he pays that has financed most of the industry's capital improvements.

26:37.320 --> 26:43.640
What are some of the results? Instead of being just a part of the general inflationary movement,

26:44.120 --> 26:49.720
the price advance in steel since World War II has been substantially greater than that of the

26:49.720 --> 26:56.520
rest of the economy. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the finished steel price increase

26:56.600 --> 27:05.080
was greater than any of the BLS wholesale commodity groups from 47 to 58, from 53 to 58,

27:05.080 --> 27:11.480
and from 56 to 58. The increase in the price of finished steel was approximately four times

27:11.480 --> 27:19.640
greater than the increase in the all commodity index from 1947 to 58. What is all this

27:19.640 --> 27:25.640
costing the people of the United States? The cost of direct bars of steel of the price

27:26.120 --> 27:32.600
between the second half of 55 and 1958 has been more than five billion dollars.

27:33.320 --> 27:38.680
This is without allowing for the pure-mitting which takes place between the direct buyer and the

27:38.680 --> 27:45.400
ultimate consumer. As we all know, when steel gets to the consumer in the form of everything from

27:45.400 --> 27:50.920
bobby pins to automobiles, the price increases have been multiplied several times.

27:51.880 --> 27:57.960
Ladies and gentlemen, I have reported to you only a few of the cold-hard facts about the price of steel.

27:58.680 --> 28:03.640
By the time you hear these words, the contract between the steel workers and the steel industry

28:03.640 --> 28:09.800
will have passed. Whether a strike is in progress at this moment or not, the facts behind this

28:09.800 --> 28:16.520
dispute are still significant and important. If making them available to the public serves to help,

28:17.160 --> 28:22.040
the steel industry solve these problems, then I am glad to have been able to present them.

28:22.040 --> 28:26.680
And let me say that I think that there is enough in this picture so that some concessions

28:26.680 --> 28:32.440
can be made both on the side of management and of the steel workers to enable them to get

28:32.440 --> 28:39.080
together on a contract which would avoid a strike and a fuller spiral in the inflationary

28:39.080 --> 28:42.680
period that we have been going through. I certainly hope that that will be the case.

28:43.240 --> 28:45.000
Thank you and goodbye until next week.

28:58.520 --> 29:00.360
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee.

29:01.080 --> 29:05.560
Last year, as you will remember, the Senate passed a good and workable self-financing bill

29:05.560 --> 29:11.000
for the Tennessee Valley Authority. We haven't had any appropriations for any new starts and

29:11.000 --> 29:17.400
major construction in the TVA since the Eisenhower administration came to office in 1953.

29:18.120 --> 29:23.800
The president himself recommended that in lieu of appropriations, we be given the right to finance

29:23.800 --> 29:29.880
ourselves in Safari's power operations and construction are concerned. The House began renewed

29:29.880 --> 29:35.560
consideration of the bill week before last. The private power lobby was out in force and conducted

29:35.560 --> 29:41.240
a vigorous campaign against it. Then this week, the House Rules Committee met and voted to deny

29:41.240 --> 29:46.360
the TVA a rule for consideration of the bill. This means that unless the Rules Committee

29:46.360 --> 29:51.960
reconsideres and I earnestly hope it will, it would take a two-thirds vote to even bring the bill

29:51.960 --> 29:57.560
up on the floor for debate. I'm heart sick over this action in the House, but I'm not giving

29:57.560 --> 30:02.760
willing to give up until the last whistle is blown on this Congress. Right now, we don't have a

30:02.760 --> 30:08.520
two-thirds vote in favor of anything for the TVA and the House. We only had two votes in our

30:08.520 --> 30:13.480
favor on the Rules Committee, but I think the Rules Committee may have completely not have

30:13.480 --> 30:18.920
completely understood the issue and therefore may reconsider. The tactics of the private

30:18.920 --> 30:24.840
power lobby, however, should now be clear for anyone to see. For years, they complained about the

30:24.840 --> 30:29.640
TVA getting appropriations, but it's clear now that they really weren't worried about those

30:29.640 --> 30:36.040
appropriations, which the TVA has always repaid on schedule with a handsome return to the government.

30:36.600 --> 30:41.400
For now, they are clearly on the record as wanting to denounce even the right to finance ourselves.

30:42.120 --> 30:46.360
They are recklessly willing to jeopardize the investment that the government already has

30:46.920 --> 30:52.520
in the TVA and the future of an entire region just to satisfy their own selfish weight.

30:53.160 --> 30:59.480
They simply want to kill the TVA as is simple as that. And then with the example of TVA gone,

30:59.960 --> 31:05.880
they want to run away with their own prices. They want again the unfettered chance to gouge the

31:05.880 --> 31:11.880
consumer. The greed of the private power lobby has brought it to grief before. And I predict that

31:11.880 --> 31:18.120
with this example reminiscent as it is of the old ensue days, the private power lobby is headed

31:18.120 --> 31:23.560
for grief again. It just doesn't know the meaning of the philosophy of live and let live.

31:24.440 --> 31:30.680
The House Rules Committee dealt a serious and perhaps mortal blow to two other good and worthwhile

31:30.680 --> 31:36.760
pieces of legislation this week. One of these was the Farm Bill. And I hope that they will reconsider

31:36.760 --> 31:43.080
that also. The House tried desperately to overrule its rules committee on the bill. And while there

31:43.080 --> 31:48.440
was a clear majority vote in favor of such action, the bill failed to get the necessary two thirds vote.

31:49.080 --> 31:54.600
As you know, I supported and worked for this Farm Bill in the Senate and it passed in the Senate.

31:54.600 --> 32:00.840
The House Agricultural Committee reported it out in substantially the same form by unanimous vote.

32:00.840 --> 32:06.360
The Rules Committee decided to use its veto. This is serious in that it means unless the bill is

32:06.360 --> 32:12.520
pried out of the House, there will be a cut in cotton acreage. It also means that the small farmer will

32:12.520 --> 32:19.320
get a further cut and some of them can't hardly survive as it is. And it delays the day when cotton

32:19.320 --> 32:24.760
will become competitive on the world market. Finally, there's the community facilities bill that

32:24.760 --> 32:30.360
I sponsored along with Senator Fulbright in the Senate. It passed the Senate. This bill would have

32:30.360 --> 32:36.520
made it possible for communities, utility districts, cities and school boards to finance local public

32:36.520 --> 32:42.200
works programs at low interest rates and over a long period of years. It would have been a great

32:42.200 --> 32:48.040
help to the economy and to giving people jobs. I can't remember anything which has creative

32:48.040 --> 32:53.320
so much interest among the local officials of Tennessee. I have letters from many, many mayors,

32:53.320 --> 32:57.960
county judges and others outlining much needed work that they would do under this program.

32:58.600 --> 33:04.600
But again, the House Rules Committee denied it a rule. All I can say is that we will try again next year.

33:05.400 --> 33:10.840
There are often disappointments in this business of legislation. You work awfully hard for

33:10.840 --> 33:16.520
something and then see it lost. But the only thing to do is to keep trying. I often think of the

33:16.520 --> 33:23.080
late Senator George Norris. He tried for years to establish the TBA only to fail repeatedly.

33:23.080 --> 33:27.960
Then finally, he had the satisfaction of seeing his dream become the greatest example of democracy

33:27.960 --> 33:36.680
and action in the world. We must never give up. Thank you and goodbye until next week.

